{"title_page": "James Hervey Otey", "text_new": "{{short description|19th-century American Episcopal bishop}}\n{{more footnotes|date=February 2017}}\n{{refimprove|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n|name= James Hervey Otey\n|honorific-prefix= The Right Reverend\n|honorific-suffix = S.T.D., D.D., LL.D.\n|image= Bishop James Hervey Otey.jpg\n|caption=\n|title= [[Episcopal Diocese of Tennessee|Bishop of Tennessee]]\n|alt=\n|order=\n|term= 1834-1863\n|term_start=\n|term_end=\n|predecessor = \n|successor = [[Charles Todd Quintard]]\n|ordination= June 7, 1827\n|ordained_by = [[John Stark Ravenscroft]]\n|consecration=January 14, 1834\n|consecrated_by = [[William White (bishop of Pennsylvania)|William White]]\n|birth_date= January 27, 1800\n|birth_place= [[Bedford County, Virginia]], [[United States]]\n|death_date= April 23, 1863 (aged 63)\n|death_place= [[Memphis, Tennessee]], [[United States]]\n|spouse= Elizabeth Davis Pannill\n|party= \n|parents = Isaac Otey & Elizabeth Mathews \n|church= [[Episcopal Church in the United States of America|Episcopal Church]]\n|religion=[[Anglicanism|Anglican]]\n|nationality = [[Americans|American]] \n}}\n\n'''James Hervey Otey''' (January 27, 1800&nbsp;\u2013 April 23, 1863), Christian educator and the first [[Episcopal Church in the United States of America|Episcopal]] Bishop of [[Episcopal Diocese of Tennessee|Tennessee]], established the [[Anglican]] church in the state and its first parish churches.\n\n==Biography==\nJames Hervey Otey was born January 27, 1800 in [[Bedford County, Virginia]] to Major Isaac Otey and [[Mathews family|Elizabeth Mathews]].<ref>Churchman Associates(1898) The Churchman, Volume 77 https://books.google.com/books?id=5GExAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA18-PA21 Retrieved September 1, 2013</ref><ref name=Boots>Boots, John R. (1970). The Mat(t)hews family: an anthology of Mathews lineages. The University of Wisconsin&nbsp;\u2014 Madison</ref> Otey attended the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]].  Upon his graduation in 1820, he was appointed as a [[tutor]] in Greek and Latin at the school.  Following his marriage to Elizabeth Davis Pannill, daughter of William Pannill and Martha Mitchell of [[Petersburg, Virginia]] in 1821, he moved to [[Maury County, Tennessee]] and became principal of a boys' school.\n\nOn returning to [[North Carolina]] to head the academy at Warrenton, Otey was baptized and confirmed in [[Episcopal Church in the United States of America|The Episcopal Church]]. He became a [[deacon]] in 1825 and priest in 1827.  He then returned to Franklin and organized Tennessee's first Episcopal church there in the [[Freemasonry|Masonic Lodge]].  He established several other churches and on July 1, 1829, established the Episcopal [[Diocese]] of Tennessee at [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]].\n\nOtey was elected the first [[bishop]] in June 1833 and was consecrated at Christ Church, [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|Philadelphia]], the following January.  Following his election, Otey also took charge of the Diocese of [[Mississippi]] and was missionary bishop for [[Arkansas]] and the [[Indian Territory]] (now [[Oklahoma]]).  He traveled for months at a time across the extensive region, establishing new churches and preaching the [[Gospel]].\n\nOtey was fervently interested in Christian education and helped organize schools at [[Ashwood, Tennessee|Ashwood]], [[Jackson, Tennessee|Jackson]] and [[Columbia, Tennessee]].  His dreams for a \"Literary and Theological Seminary\" for the region were realized when the [[University of the South]] at [[Sewanee: The University of the South|Sewanee]] was established in 1857.\n\nOtey lived at \"Mercer Hall\" in Columbia from 1835 to 1852, when he relocated to [[Memphis, Tennessee]], where in 1863 he died.<ref name=\"weeklystandardobit\">{{cite news |title=Death of Bishop Otey. |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/112299562/?terms=%22James%2BHervey%2BOtey%22 |accessdate=June 15, 2018 |work=The Weekly Standard |date=May 20, 1863|location=Raleigh, North Carolina|page=1|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=registration }}</ref> After the Civil War, he was re-buried at [[St. John's Episcopal Church (Columbia, Tennessee)|St. John's Church]] at [[Ashwood, Tennessee|Ashwood]] in Maury County.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* Richard Quin ([n.d.]). [http://tennesseeencyclopedia.net/entry.php?rec=1025 James Hervey Otey]. In: ''The Tennessee Encyclopaedia of History and Culture''. Nashville, Tennessee: Tennessee Historical Society. {{PD-notice}}&nbsp;\u2013 please see talk\n\n==External links==\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=James Hervey Otey}}\n* [http://anglicanhistory.org/usa/jhotey/ Documents by Otey] from [[Project Canterbury]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Otey, James Hervey}}\n[[Category:1800 births]]\n[[Category:1863 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sewanee: The University of the South people]]\n[[Category:People from Memphis, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Heads of universities and colleges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Bishops of the Episcopal Church in the United States of America]]\n[[Category:19th-century Anglican bishops]]\n[[Category:19th-century American Episcopalians]]\n[[Category:Episcopal Church in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Religious leaders from Tennessee]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|19th-century American Episcopal bishop}}\n{{more footnotes|date=February 2017}}\n{{refimprove|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n|name= James Hervey Otey\n|honorific-prefix= The Right Reverend\n|honorific-suffix = S.T.D., D.D., LL.D.\n|image= Bishop James Hervey Otey.jpg\n|caption=\n|title= [[Episcopal Diocese of Tennessee|Bishop of Tennessee]]\n|alt=\n|order=\n|term= 1834-1863\n|term_start=\n|term_end=\n|predecessor = \n|successor = [[Charles Todd Quintard]]\n|ordination= June 7, 1827\n|ordained_by = [[John Stark Ravenscroft]]\n|consecration=January 14, 1834\n|consecrated_by = [[William White (bishop of Pennsylvania)|William White]]\n|birth_date= January 27, 1800\n|birth_place= [[Bedford County, Virginia]], [[United States]]\n|death_date= April 23, 1863 (aged 63)\n|death_place= [[Memphis, Tennessee]], [[United States]]\n|spouse= Elizabeth Davis Pannill\n|party= \n|parents = Isaac Otey & Elizabeth Mathews \n|church= [[Episcopal Church in the United States of America|Episcopal Church]]\n|religion=[[Anglicanism|Anglican]]\n|nationality = [[Americans|American]] \n}}\n\n'''James Hervey Otey''' (January 27, 1800&nbsp;\u2013 April 23, 1863), Christian educator and the first [[Episcopal Church in the United States of America|Episcopal]] Bishop of [[Episcopal Diocese of Tennessee|Tennessee]], established the [[Anglican]] church in the state and its first parish churches.\n\n==Biography==\nJames Hervey Otey was born January 27, 1800 in [[Bedford County, Virginia]] to Major Isaac Otey and [[Mathews family (Virginia)|Elizabeth Mathews]].<ref>Churchman Associates(1898) The Churchman, Volume 77 https://books.google.com/books?id=5GExAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA18-PA21 Retrieved September 1, 2013</ref><ref name=Boots>Boots, John R. (1970). The Mat(t)hews family: an anthology of Mathews lineages. The University of Wisconsin&nbsp;\u2014 Madison</ref> Otey attended the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]].  Upon his graduation in 1820, he was appointed as a [[tutor]] in Greek and Latin at the school.  Following his marriage to Elizabeth Davis Pannill, daughter of William Pannill and Martha Mitchell of [[Petersburg, Virginia]] in 1821, he moved to [[Maury County, Tennessee]] and became principal of a boys' school.\n\nOn returning to [[North Carolina]] to head the academy at Warrenton, Otey was baptized and confirmed in [[Episcopal Church in the United States of America|The Episcopal Church]]. He became a [[deacon]] in 1825 and priest in 1827.  He then returned to Franklin and organized Tennessee's first Episcopal church there in the [[Freemasonry|Masonic Lodge]].  He established several other churches and on July 1, 1829, established the Episcopal [[Diocese]] of Tennessee at [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]].\n\nOtey was elected the first [[bishop]] in June 1833 and was consecrated at Christ Church, [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|Philadelphia]], the following January.  Following his election, Otey also took charge of the Diocese of [[Mississippi]] and was missionary bishop for [[Arkansas]] and the [[Indian Territory]] (now [[Oklahoma]]).  He traveled for months at a time across the extensive region, establishing new churches and preaching the [[Gospel]].\n\nOtey was fervently interested in Christian education and helped organize schools at [[Ashwood, Tennessee|Ashwood]], [[Jackson, Tennessee|Jackson]] and [[Columbia, Tennessee]].  His dreams for a \"Literary and Theological Seminary\" for the region were realized when the [[University of the South]] at [[Sewanee: The University of the South|Sewanee]] was established in 1857.\n\nOtey lived at \"Mercer Hall\" in Columbia from 1835 to 1852, when he relocated to [[Memphis, Tennessee]], where in 1863 he died.<ref name=\"weeklystandardobit\">{{cite news |title=Death of Bishop Otey. |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/112299562/?terms=%22James%2BHervey%2BOtey%22 |accessdate=June 15, 2018 |work=The Weekly Standard |date=May 20, 1863|location=Raleigh, North Carolina|page=1|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=registration }}</ref> After the Civil War, he was re-buried at [[St. John's Episcopal Church (Columbia, Tennessee)|St. John's Church]] at [[Ashwood, Tennessee|Ashwood]] in Maury County.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* Richard Quin ([n.d.]). [http://tennesseeencyclopedia.net/entry.php?rec=1025 James Hervey Otey]. In: ''The Tennessee Encyclopaedia of History and Culture''. Nashville, Tennessee: Tennessee Historical Society. {{PD-notice}}&nbsp;\u2013 please see talk\n\n==External links==\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=James Hervey Otey}}\n* [http://anglicanhistory.org/usa/jhotey/ Documents by Otey] from [[Project Canterbury]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Otey, James Hervey}}\n[[Category:1800 births]]\n[[Category:1863 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sewanee: The University of the South people]]\n[[Category:People from Memphis, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Heads of universities and colleges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Bishops of the Episcopal Church in the United States of America]]\n[[Category:19th-century Anglican bishops]]\n[[Category:19th-century American Episcopalians]]\n[[Category:Episcopal Church in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Religious leaders from Tennessee]]\n", "name_user": "Newtack101", "label": "safe", "comment": "updated one link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Hervey_Otey"}
